f hope she wasn't sure she even believed.Comical, provocative, and heartbreaking, Preaching in My Yes Dress tells several stories: of a child's need to cleave to the very God who instills mortal terror; of the shape-shifting that a public "pastoral identity" entails; of the power of ritual and the weight involved in presiding over it; and of the rise of the religious right and the patriarchy endemic to both scripture and faith traditions. Page also raises the question of whether or not faith can heal the wounds the life of faith has itself inflicted.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aLutheran ChurchxBiographyxClergy. 0aLutheran ChurchxClergyvBiography. 0aWomen clergyxBiographyxUnited StatesxUnited StatesxBiography. 0aWomen clergyzUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWomen clergyzUnited StatesxBiography. 4aGeneral Interest : Autobigraphy. 4aGeneral Interest : Memoir. 4aNew York/Regional : New York/Regional. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Christianity. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Personal Memoirs.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846084040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438460840423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438460840/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles